('Incline Barbell Bench Press',
 'upper_chest', array['triceps','shoulder','lats'], array['upper_chest','triceps','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','incline_bench'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Bench angled 30-45°. Lie back with shoulder blades retracted and depressed, slight arch, feet flat. Grip slightly wider than shoulder width. Lower bar to upper chest (clavicle area). Press straight up — the bar path has a slight arc from upper chest back to over mid-face. The incline shifts emphasis to the upper clavicular head of the pectoralis major — the most aesthetically important chest region.',
 'Angle too steep (>45° shifts to shoulder dominant); bar touching too low (misses upper chest focus); shoulder blades not retracted (reduces chest engagement); elbows flaring excessively.',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['30-45°: the sweet spot for upper chest','Touch the upper chest: not the neck, not the lower sternum','Retract the shoulder blades: create a platform to press from','Slight arch: this is normal and protective — not excessive'],
 array['Incline barbell press with pause','Close grip incline for upper chest and tricep','Incline press with chains for accommodation'],
 array['Incline dumbbell press (more wrist freedom)','Incline Smith machine press','Low cable fly for upper chest activation'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','incline_press','upper_chest','hypertrophy','barbell'], array['shoulder_impingement','AC_joint_pain'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 8, null, 120, true),

('Low-to-High Cable Fly (Lower Pec)',
 'chest', array['anterior_delts','biceps'], array['chest','anterior_delts'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Set cable pulleys at the lowest point. Stand in center, one foot forward, arms extended down and to the sides. Bring hands together in an arc from low to high — finishing at eye level. This trajectory targets the upper-outer pectoral fibers (clavicular head) with a full stretch at the bottom and peak contraction at the top. The cable maintains tension throughout the full arc — unlike dumbbells which lose tension at the top.',
 'Using too much weight causing shoulder dominance; not achieving full stretch at the bottom position; elbows bending excessively converting to a row; standing too far forward.',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['Slight bend in elbows: maintain throughout the arc','Tension on chest: if you feel shoulders only, adjust angle','Meet in the middle: squeeze hard at the top contraction','Feet staggered: this gives you spinal stability'],
 array['Low to high cable fly with longer holds at peak','Superset with high to low for complete chest coverage','Standing cable crossover from multiple angles'],
 array['Dumbbell fly (fixed arc)','Band fly for lighter resistance','Chest press machine for stable pressing'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','cable_fly','upper_chest','lower_chest','isolation','hypertrophy'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'transverse', false, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Dumbbell Chest Fly (45-Degree Angle)',
 'chest', array['anterior_delts','biceps'], array['chest','anterior_delts'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbells','bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Flat or slight incline bench. Start with dumbbells pressed together above chest. Slowly lower arms out to sides — maintaining a slight bend in elbows — until chest feels fully stretched (upper arm parallel to floor). Drive arms back together in a hugging arc. The fly is a pure isolation for the pectoral muscle fibers with maximum stretch. Focus: the negative is as important as the positive — 3-4 second lowering.',
 'Going too deep creating shoulder impingement at the bottom; elbows straightening (converts to shoulder exercise); using too much weight eliminating the stretch; rushing the negative (missing the hypertrophy stimulus).',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['Slight elbow bend: locked in — don''t let it increase','Stretch feeling: maximum stretch at the bottom is the goal','Control down: the lowering phase builds the muscle','Squeeze together: imagine hugging a tree on the way up'],
 array['Incline dumbbell fly for upper chest','Fly with pause at maximum stretch','Fly superset with press'],
 array['Cable fly for constant tension alternative','Pec deck machine for safety','Banded fly for home training'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','dumbbell_fly','isolation','hypertrophy','stretch'], array['shoulder_impingement','pec_strain_acute'],
 'push', 'transverse', false, 4, 12, null, 60, true),

('Guillotine Press (Wide Grip Upper Chest)',
 'upper_chest', array['shoulder','triceps'], array['upper_chest','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','flat_bench'], 'advanced', false,
 'Wide grip (outside rings) flat bench. Lower bar to neck/upper chest area (not the lower sternum as in competition bench). The wider grip and higher touch point maximally stretch the upper chest fibers. Arnold Schwarzenegger''s favourite chest builder. Use lighter weight than regular bench — the stretch position is mechanically disadvantaged. Lower controlled (4 seconds), full stretch, press.',
 'Too much weight (injury risk is higher due to stretched position); lowering too fast; bar touching the neck (should touch clavicle/upper chest); performing without adequate shoulder preparation.',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['Wider grip: outside the rings for maximum chest stretch','Touch high: clavicle area, not sternum','Light weight: this is a stretch exercise — 60% of regular bench max','Control: the slower the negative, the greater the stimulus'],
 array['Neck press with full range','Superset guillotine + close grip for full chest and tricep pump','Volume set 3x15 for hypertrophy'],
 array['Standard bench press','Incline dumbbell press','Cable fly for stretch without bar risk'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','guillotine_press','wide_grip','upper_chest','advanced'], array['shoulder_impingement','AC_joint_pain','rotator_cuff_weakness'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 10, null, 90, true),

('Machine Chest Fly (Pec Deck)',
 'chest', array['anterior_delts'], array['chest','anterior_delts'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['pec_deck_machine'], 'beginner', false,
 'Adjust seat so elbows are at shoulder height with pads touching forearms. Bring arms together in a hugging motion. Hold 2 seconds at peak contraction. Return slowly with control. The pec deck is the safest chest isolation movement — fixed arc removes instability variables. Ideal for beginners learning the chest mind-muscle connection, and for advanced bodybuilders finishing pumps.',
 'Seat too high (causes shoulder joint stress); slamming the weight stack on the return (loses eccentric); not squeezing at the peak; using too much momentum.',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['Seat height: elbows at shoulder height','Squeeze: 2-second peak contraction — feel the chest','Slow return: the weight should not clank','Mind-muscle: focus on the pec contracting, not the movement'],
 array['Pec deck with longer peak holds','Heavy pec deck for strength','Superset pec deck + push-up for pump'],
 array['Cable fly for greater range of motion','Band fly at home','Dumbbell fly for free weight version'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','pec_deck','isolation','beginner_friendly','machine'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'transverse', false, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Decline Barbell Bench Press',
 'lower_chest', array['triceps','shoulder'], array['lower_chest','triceps','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','decline_bench'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Decline bench (30° below flat). Feet hooked on the bench pad. Lower bar to lower sternum/upper abs. Press. The decline angle shifts emphasis to the lower pectoral fibers and the sternal head of the chest. Also allows slightly more weight than flat bench due to favorable shoulder mechanics. The lower chest is often underdeveloped — decline pressing and dips directly target this region.',
 'Too steep a decline causing blood rush to head; bar touching too high (removes lower chest bias); gripping too narrow; not securing feet before pressing heavy.',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['Lower sternum touch: the angle determines where you touch','Secure feet: safety first on decline','Can use more weight: the decline mechanics are advantageous','Lower chest is often lagging: this is the prescription'],
 array['Decline with close grip for tricep emphasis','Decline dumbbell press for independent loading','Decline cable press for constant tension'],
 array['Flat bench press as baseline','Push-up with feet elevated','Dips for lower chest alternative'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','decline_press','lower_chest','hypertrophy','barbell'], array['blood_pressure_issues','vertigo','shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 10, null, 90, true),

('Cable Crossover',
 'chest', array['anterior_delts','biceps'], array['chest','anterior_delts'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Stand in the center between two high cables. Arms extended to sides with slight elbow bend. Bring hands together in a downward arc finishing crossed in front of the hips. The crossing of the hands adds additional peak contraction. Variations: (1) Cross high (for lower chest, brings hands down to hips). (2) Cross level (for mid chest). (3) Cross low to high (for upper chest). The cable maintains tension throughout the entire arc.',
 'Bending elbows more than a slight angle (converts to row/pull); not completing the cross (losing peak contraction); too much trunk lean forward; using too much weight sacrificing the arc.',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['Cross your hands: right hand crosses to left side at finish','Slight bend only: your arms are curved beams, not bent poles','Standing tall: let the chest do the work','Three angles: change crossover height to hit different chest regions'],
 array['Single arm cable crossover for unilateral focus','Cable crossover drop set','Superset cable crossover + press'],
 array['Dumbbell fly','Band crossover','Pec deck machine'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','cable_crossover','isolation','hypertrophy','cable'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'transverse', false, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Chest Dip (Forward Lean)',
 'lower_chest', array['triceps','shoulder'], array['lower_chest','triceps','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dip_bars'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Parallel bar dip with forward lean. Lean forward 20-30° from vertical during the dip. Lower until shoulders are slightly below elbow height. Drive up. The forward lean shifts emphasis from triceps (upright dip) to lower chest (leaned dip). Use bodyweight or add weight with a dip belt. Considered one of the best lower chest exercises in bodybuilding.',
 'Not leaning forward enough (stays tricep dominant); allowing elbows to flare excessively; not reaching adequate depth; leaning too far forward (shoulder stress).',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['Forward lean 20-30°: this shifts the load to the lower chest','Elbows at 45-60°: not straight back, not straight out','Depth: shoulder at elbow height or just below','Control: no swinging or momentum — pure chest work'],
 array['Weighted dip with belt','Dip superset with cable crossover','Ring dip for instability challenge'],
 array['Assisted dip machine','Band-assisted dip','Elevated push-up for similar angle'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','dip','lower_chest','compound','hypertrophy'], array['shoulder_impingement','tricep_tendon_irritation'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 10, null, 90, true),

('Push-Up Variations for Hypertrophy',
 'chest', array['triceps','shoulder','core'], array['chest','triceps','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['bodyweight','plates','push_up_handles'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Advanced push-up variations for chest hypertrophy: (1) Weighted push-up: plates on back 4x15. (2) Deficit push-up (hands on elevated handles): deeper stretch 4x12. (3) Archer push-up: one arm wide, one narrow, alternate 3x8 each. (4) Clapping push-up: explosive for power 3x10. (5) Wide push-up: maximally stretches pec 4x15. Each variation targets slightly different pectoral fibers. Use as finishers or accessory work.',
 'Not modifying hand position (hands at 45° to body for best chest activation); hips rising creating poor loading; not going to chest touch; rushing the eccentric.',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['Hands at 45°: not straight ahead, not straight out','Chest to floor: full range every rep','Wide base: more chest than narrow','Add weight: when bodyweight is easy, load it'],
 array['One-arm push-up','Planche push-up for advanced','Push-up on rings for instability'],
 array['Knee push-up for beginners','Wall push-up for complete beginners','Incline push-up (easier angle)'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','push_up','hypertrophy','bodyweight','variation'], array['wrist_injury'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Sternal Crunch (Chest-Focused Core)',
 'chest', array['core','shoulder'], array['chest','core'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Often performed but misunderstood: the chest stretch is also a chest contraction pattern. Standing cable crunch: pull cable from overhead, crunch torso downward driving elbows toward the floor while fully rounding the upper back. Targets the lower pec sternal fibers through a crunching arc. Also: manual sternal crunch — hands interlaced behind head, crunch forward rounding the upper back maximally. Targets the sternal/costal head of the pectoralis.',
 'Confusing with a standard cable crunch (different cue: drive elbows down, not just crunch forward); not rounding the upper back (the rounding stretches and contracts the lower pec).',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['Elbows drive toward the floor: that is the cue','Upper back rounds: this is intended for chest activation','Feel the sternal head contract: under and inside','Lighter cable: feel the muscle, not move the weight'],
 array['Cable chest crunch with higher resistance','Pec minor isolation work','Chest isolation program comprehensive'],
 array['Standard dumbbell fly','Pec deck isolation','Cable crossover middle height'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','sternal_crunch','lower_chest','cable','isolation'], array['lower_back_pain'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 3, 15, null, 60, true),

('Chest Pre-Exhaustion Superset',
 'chest', array['triceps','shoulder'], array['chest','triceps','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['pec_deck_machine','barbell','bench'], 'advanced', false,
 'Pre-exhaustion technique: fatigue the chest with an isolation movement, then immediately perform a compound press. Example: Pec deck fly 15 reps → immediately flat barbell bench press 8 reps. The pec is pre-fatigued so triceps and shoulders cannot compensate. Another version: cable fly → dumbbell press. Use: 3 supersets, rest 90 seconds between. This technique maximizes pectoral recruitment on the compound movement.',
 'Using too much weight on the compound movement after the pre-exhaust (the chest will be significantly fatigued); not transitioning immediately between exercises (defeats the pre-exhaust); not reducing ego and weight for the compound.',
 'chest_hypertrophy', array['Transition immediately: no rest between isolation and compound','Less weight on the press: pre-exhausted muscle equals lighter loads needed','Feel the chest fail: that is the entire point','Advanced technique: master the movements individually first'],
 array['Extended pre-exhaust with 3 isolation exercises','Reverse pre-exhaust (compound then isolation)','Complete chest workout using pre-exhaust for all sets'],
 array['Regular superset (pressing + pressing)','Straight sets for muscle mass foundation','Individual exercises mastered first'],
 array['bodybuilding','chest','pre_exhaustion','superset','advanced','hypertrophy_technique'], array['shoulder_injury'],
 'push', 'transverse', false, 3, null, null, 90, true);


