('Meadows Row (Landmine Single-Arm Row)',
 'back', array['biceps','rear_deltoid'], array['back','biceps','rear_deltoid'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','landmine'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Named after John Meadows. Set up landmine at floor level. Stand perpendicular, staggered stance with same-side foot back. Grip the end of the sleeve near the collar with the outside hand. Row with a pulling-up-and-back motion, elbow flaring slightly out (30-45°) to target upper-back thickness. Allow a full stretch at the bottom — lat, rhomboid, and rear delt all get maximum lengthening. Pull explosively, squeeze at the top, lower slowly.',
 'Standing too close to the landmine (reduces range of motion); using a supinated grip instead of overhand (changes target muscles); not allowing the shoulder to protract at the bottom; using too much body English on heavy sets.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Elbow flares 30-45°: not tucked, not fully out','Shoulder protracts at the bottom: full stretch','Pull toward the hip: not straight up','Stagger stance: rear foot same side as working arm'],
 array['Meadows row with added resistance','Reverse-grip Meadows row for lower lat','Meadows row dropset protocol'],
 array['Single-arm dumbbell row on bench','Chest-supported row machine','Cable single-arm row seated'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','meadows_row','landmine','upper_back','thickness'], array['shoulder_injury','lower_back_pain'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', true, 4, 10, null, 90, true),

('Chest-Supported Row (Prone)',
 'back', array['biceps','rear_deltoid'], array['back','biceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','incline_bench'], 'beginner', true,
 'Set incline bench to 30-45°. Lie face-down (prone) with chest supported. Hold dumbbells and row with both arms simultaneously. Because the chest is supported, lower back is eliminated — pure back work. Elbows track at 45-60° from the body. Squeeze rhomboids and mid-traps at the top. Lower with control. Excellent for beginners learning to feel the back work without lower back fatigue compromising the set.',
 'Shrugging the shoulders (engaging upper traps instead of mid-back); swinging the arms without scapular retraction; not squeezing at the top; using too much weight and losing control.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Chest stays on pad: eliminate lower back','Elbows 45-60° angle: not fully tucked or flared','Squeeze shoulder blades together at top','Slow negative: 3 count down'],
 array['Barbell bent-over row standing','Chest-supported row machine with full range','Single-arm chest-supported dumbbell row'],
 array['Seated cable row','Lat pulldown','Band pull-apart'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','chest_supported_row','prone','isolation','beginners'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 12, null, 75, true),

('Straight-Arm Pulldown (Lat Isolation)',
 'back', array['triceps_long_head','core'], array['back','triceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine','bar_attachment'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Cable pulley set high. Grip bar or rope with straight arms, slightly wider than shoulder-width. Hinge forward at the hips 30-45°. With arms STRAIGHT (no elbow bend), pull the bar down and back in an arc until it touches your thighs. This movement isolates the latissimus dorsi without bicep involvement. Squeeze the lats hard at the bottom, then control the eccentric slowly back overhead. Rope variation allows greater range. Load: moderate weight, high reps.',
 'Bending the elbows (turning it into a pulldown — defeats the isolation purpose); rounding the upper back; not hinging forward at the hips; not feeling the lats at the top stretch.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Arms stay straight: the entire point of this exercise','Hinge forward: 30-45° at the hips for proper arc','Feel the lat at the top: full overhead stretch','Rope version: split at bottom for even more stretch'],
 array['Weighted dip belt straight-arm pulldown','Full ROM overhead cable straight-arm pull','Incorporate into pre-exhaust for lat-focused workouts'],
 array['Kneeling straight-arm pulldown','Resistance band lat pullover','Dumbbell pullover lying on bench'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','straight_arm_pulldown','lat_isolation','cable','no_bicep'], array['elbow_tendinopathy'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Close-Grip Supinated Pulldown',
 'back', array['biceps','rhomboids'], array['back','biceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine','v_bar'], 'beginner', true,
 'Use a V-bar or close-grip supinated attachment. Sit at lat pulldown machine. Grip with palms facing you, hands 6-10 inches apart. Pull toward the upper chest, driving elbows down and back. The supinated (underhand) grip activates the lower lat more effectively and allows the biceps to assist through a mechanically advantageous position. Full stretch at the top, full contraction at the bottom. Lean back slightly (10-15°) to maintain lat emphasis.',
 'Leaning back excessively (turns into a row); pulling too low past the chest; not allowing full overhead stretch at the top; using momentum and body swing.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Supinate the grip: palms face you for lower lat','Elbows drive down: not just pull the bar','Lean 10-15°: minimal, not 45° lean-back rowing','Full stretch at top: do not cut the range of motion'],
 array['Weighted close-grip pulldown','Single-arm cable pulldown with supination','Incorporate into pre-exhaust sequence'],
 array['Wide-grip pulldown (easier lat feel)','Assisted pulldown machine','Resistance band lat pulldown'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','close_grip','supinated','pulldown','lower_lat'], array['bicep_tendinopathy'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 10, null, 75, true),

('Dumbbell Pullover (Lat & Serratus)',
 'back', array['chest','serratus','triceps_long_head'], array['back','chest','serratus'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Lie perpendicular across a bench with only the upper back supported. Hips drop down (creates a lat and chest stretch). Hold one dumbbell with both hands, arms extended above the chest. Lower the dumbbell in an arc overhead toward the floor, feeling the lat, serratus, and long head of tricep stretch. Pull back to starting position. Historically called "the squat for the upper body" for its ribcage expansion claims. Primarily targets lats and serratus anterior.',
 'Not dropping the hips (reduces the stretch arc); bending elbows too much (turns into a tricep extension); going too heavy and losing control behind the head; holding breath.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Hips drop: bench only supports upper back','Arms slightly bent: not straight, not heavily bent','Feel the lat and serratus: focus internally','Arc the weight: pull back through the arc, not straight up'],
 array['Cable pullover single-arm kneeling','Machine pullover (Nautilus style)','Barbell pullover for more range'],
 array['Dumbbell flat chest fly (similar position)','Resistance band pullover anchored low','Lat stretch overhead manual'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','pullover','serratus','lat_stretch','compound_isolation'], array['shoulder_impingement','lower_back_pain'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 3, 12, null, 75, true),

('Rack Pull (Partial Deadlift for Back Thickness)',
 'back', array['glutes','hamstrings','traps'], array['back','glutes','hamstrings','traps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','power_rack'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Set safety bars in a power rack at knee height or just above. Load the barbell. Stand with feet hip-width, grip just outside hips (double overhand or mixed). The partial range — knee to lockout — allows significantly more weight than full deadlift, overloading the erector spinae, upper back, and traps at the top range. Drive through the floor, keep the bar close to the body, lock out fully with glutes and upper back squeezed. DO NOT hyperextend at lockout. Controlled descent.',
 'Hyperextending the lower back at lockout; rounding the upper back under supramaximal loads; setting the pins too low (becomes a full deadlift); dropping the bar (time under tension is lost).',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Bar stays close: drag up the thighs if necessary','Lock out fully: glutes and upper back squeeze','Brace the core maximally: this is a heavy partial','No hyperextension: neutral lumbar at top'],
 array['Full competition deadlift','Block pull from floor','Romanian deadlift for hamstring focus'],
 array['Romanian deadlift','Trap bar deadlift','Hip hinge with kettlebell'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','rack_pull','partial_deadlift','trap_thickness','overload'], array['lower_back_disc','spinal_stenosis'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 5, null, 180, true),

('Seated Cable Row with Handle Variations',
 'back', array['biceps','rear_deltoid'], array['back','biceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine','seated_row'], 'beginner', true,
 'Seated at cable row station. Variations: (1) V-bar/neutral grip — targets middle back equally. (2) Wide grip/overhand — emphasizes upper back and rear deltoids. (3) Single-arm with rotation — allows greater range and serratus activation. Keep chest up, shoulders packed down, slight lean-back at the squeeze, slight lean-forward at the stretch. Drive elbows back toward the hips, not the armpits. Full protraction (arms fully extended forward) at the start to load the serratus and mid-trap.',
 'Rounding the back and using lower back momentum; pulling to the stomach rather than the lower chest; not fully extending at the start (losing the stretch); shrugging the traps.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Elbows go back toward hips: not the armpits','Full stretch forward: let the shoulders protract','Squeeze: drive the shoulder blades together at the end','Upright torso: small deliberate lean, not a swing'],
 array['Single-arm cable row standing','Machine row with plate loading','Chest-supported row machine'],
 array['Band seated row','TRX row bodyweight','Resistance band face pull'],
