('Face Pull (Rear Delt & External Rotation)',
 'back', array['rear_deltoid','rotator_cuff','rhomboids'], array['back','shoulder','rotator_cuff'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine','rope_attachment'], 'beginner', false,
 'Cable set at face height or slightly above. Use rope attachment. Grip each end with thumbs pointing behind you (not over the top). Pull the rope to face level, pulling the rope ends apart as you pull back (external rotation emphasized). Elbows should be at or above shoulder height and pointing out wide. At the end position: hands are beside the ears or slightly behind, and the shoulders are fully externally rotated. This is a corrective and strengthening exercise for the rear delt and rotator cuff.',
 'Pulling too heavy and losing the external rotation (it becomes a row); elbows dropping below shoulder height; not separating the rope ends at the finish; using the upper traps to shrug.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Elbows above shoulders: the critical cue','Rope apart: actively spread the rope ends at the finish','Thumbs back: external rotation grip from the start','Light and controlled: this is a health exercise, not a show exercise'],
 array['Face pull with added external rotation pause','TYI cable variations for rotator cuff','Band pull-apart behind neck'],
 array['Band face pull (lighter resistance)','Dumbbell rear delt fly prone','Manual external rotation with band'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','face_pull','rear_delt','rotator_cuff','corrective','health'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'pull', 'transverse', false, 3, 20, null, 60, true),

('T-Bar Row (Chest Supported Machine)',
 'back', array['biceps','rear_deltoid'], array['back','biceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['t_bar_machine'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Chest-supported T-bar: lie prone on the pad. Grip the handles (neutral or overhand). Row with elbows at 45-60° from the body, driving toward the ceiling. Squeeze the mid-back hard at the top. This machine variant completely eliminates lower back stress. Hammer Strength-style machines allow independent arm movement, which improves unilateral development. Use controlled tempo — 2 seconds up, 1 second squeeze, 3 seconds down.',
 'Shrugging the traps instead of retracting the scapulae; not getting a full range of motion from the top; bouncing the weight stack; not adjusting the pad height for proper chest support.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Chest stays on the pad: just like chest-supported dumbbell row','Scapular retraction: not just arm pull','Control the descent: 3-count negative','Feel mid-back: rhomboids and mid-traps squeezing'],
 array['Plate-loaded T-bar row standing with chest pad','Barbell landmine T-bar row','Heavy T-bar row for mass'],
 array['Seated cable row','Resistance band row','Dumbbell row single arm'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','t_bar_row','chest_supported','mid_back','machine'], array['lower_back_pain'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 10, null, 90, true),

('Snatch-Grip Deadlift for Back Width',
 'back', array['glutes','hamstrings','traps'], array['back','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell'], 'advanced', true,
 'Snatch-grip: hands as wide as possible on the bar (outside the power rings, or wherever a full squat snatch would be caught). This wide grip forces the torso lower at the start, increasing the range of motion and creating more lat, upper back, and trap involvement through a greater range. Feet hip-width. Pull as in a conventional deadlift but the bar must travel further due to the wide grip and lower start position. Builds upper back and trapezius width dramatically. Often done as a supplemental movement.',
 'Using a grip that is not truly wide (defeats the purpose); rounding the upper back without adequate upper-back strength; not using straps (grip fatigue kills the set before back fatigue); starting too upright.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Maximum width grip: use straps — grip will fail before back','Lower start: hips drop due to wide grip','Upper back tight: this is a massive spinal erector exercise','Short sets: 3-5 reps, this is not a high-rep movement'],
 array['Snatch-grip Romanian deadlift','Snatch-grip high pull','Competition snatch for full technical expression'],
 array['Conventional deadlift','Trap bar deadlift','Romanian deadlift'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','snatch_grip_deadlift','width','upper_back','advanced','traps'], array['lower_back_disc','shoulder_hypermobility'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 4, null, 180, true),

('Unilateral Low Row Machine',
 'back', array['biceps','rear_deltoid'], array['back','biceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['low_row_machine'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit at low row machine facing the weight stack. Use single-arm handle. Row one arm at a time, allowing the torso to rotate slightly with each pull. This slight rotation allows greater range of motion and serratus activation. Elbows track along the torso. Squeeze the lat and lower trapezius at the completion. Slow return. The independent arm action corrects left/right imbalances. Use controlled weight — this is not the place for ego loading.',
 'Excessive torso rotation (becomes a twist, not a row); not using full range; shrugging the shoulder; using both arms simultaneously (defeats the purpose of the unilateral machine).',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['One arm: let the other side rest completely','Slight rotation allowed: not excessive','Elbow tracks the torso: not flaring out','Squeeze: hold 1 second at the contracted position'],
 array['Single-arm cable row standing','Dumbbell row with rotation','Hammer Strength low row'],
 array['Bilateral low row','Seated cable row','Resistance band row'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','unilateral','low_row','machine','balance_correction'], array['lower_back_pain'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', true, 4, 12, null, 75, true),

('Kelso Shrug (Lying Prone Scapular Retraction)',
 'back', array['rhomboids','mid_traps'], array['back'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','incline_bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Lie prone on an incline bench set to 30-45°. Hold dumbbells hanging straight down. Without bending the elbows, retract and depress the shoulder blades — pulling them together and downward. Hold 2 seconds. Release and allow the shoulders to fully protract. This is a scapular retraction isolation exercise that specifically targets the rhomboids and mid-trapezius with zero involvement from the arms or biceps. Excellent for posture correction and mid-back density.',
 'Bending the elbows (it becomes a row — biceps take over); not achieving full protraction at the start; rushing the movement; using heavy dumbbells (the ROM is small; light weight forces full control).',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Arms absolutely straight: any bend changes the exercise','Shoulder blades together and DOWN: not just back','2-second hold: feel the mid-back squeeze','Light weight: you will feel this with 10 kg, not 30 kg'],
 array['Kelso shrug with heavier loading','Scapular retraction with cable standing','Face pull superset with Kelso shrug'],
 array['Band pull-apart','Scapular push-up in reverse','Manual resistance scapular retraction'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','kelso_shrug','scapular_retraction','rhomboids','posture'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'pull', 'transverse', false, 3, 15, null, 60, true),

('Hatfield Row (Cambered Bar Row)',
 'back', array['biceps','rear_deltoid'], array['back','biceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cambered_bar','power_rack'], 'advanced', true,
 'Use a safety squat bar or cambered bar hanging in a power rack at hip height. Grip the camber handles. Hinge forward and row from a supported position. The cambered bar allows the hands to travel further behind the body than a straight barbell, creating extreme range of motion and a deep lat and rhomboid stretch. Can also be done while supported by a rack post. The unique bar path creates a rowing stimulus impossible with straight bars.',
 'Not having access to the correct equipment (a straight bar simply cannot replicate this); over-gripping; not using the extra range the cambered bar provides; using too much weight initially.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Use the range: the bar is designed to go deeper than normal','Hinge maximally: this is what the cambered bar is for','Elbows drive back: lead with the elbow, not the wrist','New exercise: use 40-50% of normal row weight to start'],
 array['Heavier Hatfield row with belt','Hatfield row plus pause at full stretch','Add bands to cambered bar row'],
 array['Standard barbell bent-over row','Chest-supported row','Cable row seated'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','hatfield_row','cambered_bar','advanced','range_of_motion'], array['lower_back_pain','shoulder_impingement'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 8, null, 120, true),

('Back Double Bicep Pose Training (Lat Spread)',
 'back', array['rhomboids','rear_deltoid'], array['back','rear_deltoid'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['bodyweight'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Competition posing practice and lat activation drill. Stand with arms raised at shoulder height, elbows bent at 90°. Pull the elbows down and back hard while spreading the lats maximally — visualize making your waist look smaller by pushing the lats out and down. Hold 10 seconds, relax, repeat. This practice teaches lat-mind connection, critical for bodybuilders. Also useful for activating lats before heavy compound exercises. Practice in a mirror to see lat spread width.',
 'Not actually contracting the lats (just raising the arms — the lats must be activated consciously); not practicing consistently (posing is a skill requiring training); holding breath during the pose.',
 'back_hypertrophy', array['Lats down and out: imagine armpits touching the floor','Elbows drive back: rear delt hard, create the double-bicep look','Breathe through the pose: do not hold your breath','Mirror practice: visual feedback is essential for posing'],
 array['Full competition back pose routine','Back pose with added coaching critique session','Lat spread combined with vacuum pose for separation'],
 array['Basic lat spread practice','Lat activation drills before training','Resistance band lat activation'],
 array['bodybuilding','back','posing','lat_spread','competition','mind_muscle'], array[],
 'isometric', 'frontal', false, 5, null, 10, 30, true);

