('Arnold Press (Full-Arc Shoulder Press)',
 'shoulder', array['triceps','upper_traps'], array['shoulder','triceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Named after Arnold Schwarzenegger. Start with dumbbells at shoulder height, palms facing you (supinated). As you press overhead, rotate the palms forward (pronated) so at the top position, palms face away. Reverse on descent. This rotation recruits the front, side, and rear deltoid through a greater arc than a standard press. The rotation also engages the rotator cuff dynamically. Use moderate weight — the rotation is the stimulus, not the load.',
 'Rushing the rotation (the arc is the point of the exercise); going too heavy and losing control of the rotation; not completing the rotation fully; arching the lower back excessively.',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['Slow rotation: do not rush the turning motion','Full arc: palm forward at the top, palm back at the bottom','Moderate weight: 60-70% of what you can standard press','Feel all three heads: the rotation targets them differently'],
 array['Single-arm Arnold press for core anti-rotation','Arnold press with pause at each end of rotation','Heavier Arnold press as strength progresses'],
 array['Standard dumbbell shoulder press','Seated dumbbell press with backrest','Machine shoulder press'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','arnold_press','rotation','all_heads','classical'], array['shoulder_impingement','rotator_cuff'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 10, null, 90, true),

('Lateral Raise – Cable (Constant Tension)',
 'shoulder', array['upper_traps'], array['shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine'], 'beginner', false,
 'Cable set at low position. Stand sideways to the cable. Grip the handle with the hand furthest from the cable (cross-body start). Raise the arm laterally, keeping a slight elbow bend. The cable provides CONSTANT tension through the full arc, unlike dumbbells which have zero tension at the bottom. This makes cable laterals superior for hypertrophy. Do all reps on one side, then switch. At the top, the hand is at shoulder height — do not raise higher (upper trap takes over).',
 'Raising above shoulder height; using momentum and a body swing; bending the elbow too much (it becomes a row not a raise); gripping from the same side as the cable (lose the cross-body stretch at the bottom).',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['Cross-body start: stand opposite side to cable','Shoulder height stop: not higher or the traps take over','Slight elbow bend: 10-15°, not more','Constant tension: the cable advantage over dumbbells'],
 array['Leaning cable lateral raise (even more range)','Cable lateral raise with pause at top','Bilateral cable lateral raise from V-stance'],
 array['Dumbbell lateral raise','Resistance band lateral raise','Machine lateral raise'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','cable_lateral_raise','constant_tension','side_delt','hypertrophy'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'frontal', true, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Behind-Neck Press (Smith Machine)',
 'shoulder', array['triceps','upper_traps'], array['shoulder','triceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['smith_machine'], 'advanced', false,
 'Smith machine provides a guided path, reducing instability. Sit facing away from the Smith bar. Position the bar at upper ear level. Unrack and lower to behind the neck — the bar travels to the occiput (base of the skull). Press back up. This movement overloads the lateral and rear deltoid at the bottom while the front delt dominates the press. NOTE: This exercise has a high injury risk for people with poor shoulder mobility. Only suitable for athletes with full overhead ROM and no shoulder impingement history.',
 'Forcing the movement without adequate shoulder flexibility (severe injury risk); lowering too fast; not using the Smith machine (requires full control of the path); any neck pain (stop immediately).',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['Smith bar guides: do not attempt with free barbell initially','Bar to occiput: base of skull, not top of head','Controlled descent: this position is vulnerable','Mobility required: screen for shoulder impingement first'],
 array['Behind-neck press with barbell (advanced)','Behind-neck press with additional resistance band','Wide-grip behind-neck jerk for power'],
 array['Standard overhead press','Dumbbell press neutral grip','Landmine press (shoulder-friendly)'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','behind_neck_press','smith_machine','lateral_delt','advanced'], array['shoulder_impingement','rotator_cuff','cervical_spine'],
 'push', 'frontal', false, 3, 8, null, 120, true),

('Prone Y-T-W-L Raises',
 'shoulder', array['rotator_cuff','rhomboids','rear_deltoid'], array['shoulder','back','rotator_cuff'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','incline_bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Lie prone on a slight incline (15-30°) or flat. Hold very light dumbbells (2-5 kg). Perform four shapes: Y = raise arms to a Y position at 45° overhead; T = raise arms straight out to the sides; W = retract scapulae, bend elbows to 90°, pull back into a W; L = from the W position, externally rotate so hands go from pointing forward to pointing at the ceiling. Each shape targets a different component of the posterior shoulder and rotator cuff. Strictly rehabilitative and corrective. Key for posture.',
 'Using too much weight (this is a corrective exercise, not a strength exercise); not completing all four positions; not focusing on scapular retraction in the W and L positions; performing rapidly without control.',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['Very light weight: 2-5 kg maximum','All four letters: Y, T, W, L in sequence','Hold 2 seconds each: slow and controlled','Prone position: face down eliminates momentum'],
 array['Incline Y-T-W with moderate resistance','Band Y-T-W standing for higher reps','Face pull superset with Y-T-W'],
 array['Band pull-apart','Face pull light resistance','Manual resistance rotator cuff'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','ytw','prone','rotator_cuff','corrective','posture'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'pull', 'transverse', false, 3, 10, null, 60, true),

('Dumbbell Rear Delt Fly (Bent Over)',
 'shoulder', array['rhomboids','mid_traps'], array['shoulder','back'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand with feet hip-width. Hinge forward at the hips to nearly parallel — or sit at the end of a bench and lean forward. Arms hang down with slight elbow bend. Raise both arms laterally in an arc until arms are parallel to the floor — the motion is like opening wings. The rear deltoid, rhomboids, and mid-traps work. Do NOT shrug. Do NOT raise above horizontal. Squeeze the rear delts at the top and control the descent. Focus on mind-muscle connection, not weight.',
 'Shrugging the traps and turning it into an upper-trap movement; raising too high above parallel; using momentum (swinging the torso); bending the elbows too much and turning it into a row.',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['Arms parallel to floor: stop there — no higher','Slight elbow bend: fixed throughout','Lead with the elbows: not the wrists','Mind-muscle: feel the rear delt, not the traps'],
 array['Cable rear delt fly on cables','Prone rear delt fly on incline bench','Machine rear delt fly (pec deck reverse)'],
 array['Band pull-apart standing','Face pull light','Resistance band rear delt fly'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','rear_delt_fly','bent_over','posterior_shoulder','dumbbell'], array['lower_back_pain'],
 'pull', 'transverse', false, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Upright Row (Barbell & Cable)',
 'shoulder', array['biceps','upper_traps'], array['shoulder','traps','biceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','cable_machine'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Grip the bar shoulder-width (NOT narrow — narrow grip is an impingement risk). Pull the bar vertically from hip level to chin level, leading with the elbows (elbows rise first and higher than the hands). At the top, elbows are above the bar and at chin height. Lower slowly. The shoulder-width grip ensures the elbows stay out to the sides and the lateral deltoid is targeted along with the upper traps. Cable version provides constant tension. Do not use narrow grip — this internally rotates the shoulder dangerously.',
 'Narrow grip (high impingement risk — NEVER narrow); pulling with the wrists/hands rather than leading with the elbows; not reaching the chin with the bar; shrugging instead of pulling the bar up.',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['Shoulder-width or wider: never narrow grip','Elbows lead and rise higher than the bar','Bar reaches chin height: not just neck level','Cable version: same width, smoother resistance'],
 array['Dumbbell upright row (each arm independently)','Cable upright row with wider grip','Snatch-grip upright row for more trap emphasis'],
 array['Band upright row','Face pull (similar rear delt targeting)','Machine lateral raise'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','upright_row','lateral_delt','traps','compound'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'pull', 'frontal', false, 4, 12, null, 75, true),

('Leaning Lateral Raise (Extended ROM)',
 'shoulder', array['upper_traps'], array['shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','cable_machine'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Hold a fixed support with one hand (power rack, cable column). Lean away from the support, creating a tilted body angle (20-30°). Raise the dumbbell with the free arm laterally. The lean creates a greater range of motion at the bottom of the lift — the arm can cross in front of the body at the start — and a greater stretch on the side delt. Cables preferred (constant tension). This extended-range lateral raise is superior to the standard version for hypertrophy due to increased time under tension through the stretched position.',
 'Not leaning enough (defeats the purpose); letting go of the anchor (lose balance); using too much weight (lose control through the extended range); raising above shoulder height.',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['Lean 20-30°: significant lean, not just a tilt','Cross in front at the bottom: maximum stretch position','Shoulder height at the top: stop there','Anchor firmly: hold the rack or cable column tightly'],
 array['Seated cable lateral raise with full lean','Leaning lateral raise with pause at stretch','Band leaning lateral raise for higher reps'],
 array['Standard dumbbell lateral raise','Cable lateral raise upright','Machine lateral raise'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','leaning_lateral_raise','extended_rom','side_delt','stretch'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'frontal', true, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Plate Front Raise',
 'shoulder', array['upper_chest'], array['shoulder','chest'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['weight_plate'], 'beginner', false,
 'Hold a weight plate with both hands at 3 and 9 o''clock positions (not the hole — grip the rim at the sides). Arms straight or with slight elbow bend. Raise the plate from hip level to eye level, then lower under control. The circular nature of the plate forces a neutral grip throughout, which is more shoulder-friendly than a pronated barbell front raise. The wide hold also activates the inner pectorals. Light weight: this is an isolation exercise, not a show of strength.',
 'Raising above eye level (shoulder impingement risk at extreme elevation); using momentum and swinging the torso; bending the elbows excessively; gripping the center hole (wrong position).',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['Hold the plate rim at 3 and 9: not the center hole','Eye level max: stop here for shoulder health','Arms straight or slight bend: controlled throughout','Slow descent: 3 counts down — resist gravity'],
 array['Plate front raise with rotation (internally rotate at top)','Dumbbell front raise alternating','Barbell front raise for more overload'],
 array['Cable front raise light weight','Resistance band front raise','Dumbbell front raise one at a time'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','front_raise','plate','anterior_delt','neutral_grip'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 3, 15, null, 60, true),

('Shoulder Giant Set Protocol',
 'shoulder', array['triceps','upper_traps'], array['shoulder','triceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','cable_machine'], 'advanced', false,
 'Giant set: perform 4 exercises back-to-back with no rest, then rest 2 minutes. Example giant set: (1) Dumbbell front raise × 12 → (2) Dumbbell lateral raise × 12 → (3) Bent-over rear delt fly × 12 → (4) Dumbbell overhead press × 10. This hits all three deltoid heads and compounds fatigue. Use 40-50% of normal weights. Goal: maximum muscle fiber recruitment through metabolic stress and accumulated fatigue. Excellent as a finishing superset for shoulders after heavy pressing.',
 'Using too much weight (the giant set is meant for pump and metabolic stress, not strength); resting between exercises (defeats the giant set); skipping the rear delt component (the most neglected head); performing giant sets for warm-up (these belong at the end of a session).',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['All three heads: front, lateral, rear — in the giant set','No rest between exercises: transition immediately','40-50% weight: ego check required here','Finish the session: giant sets are for ending, not starting'],
 array['Extended giant set with 6 exercises','Shoulder giant set with cables only','Superset each giant set with shoulder press'],
 array['Standard shoulder supersets','Straight sets for shoulder size','Circuit training with moderate weight'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','giant_set','all_heads','metabolic','advanced','finishing'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'multi', false, 4, 12, null, 120, true),

('Machine Lateral Raise (Fixed Path)',
 'shoulder', array['upper_traps'], array['shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['lateral_raise_machine'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit at the lateral raise machine and adjust the seat height so the pivot point aligns with the shoulder joint. Grip the handles or place elbows on the pads (depends on machine design). Raise the arms to shoulder height. The machine provides a guided path and consistent resistance through the arc. Useful for beginners learning the movement pattern, for dropsets (easy to reduce weight quickly), and for people with shoulder issues that cannot control free weights through the full range.',
 'Seat height wrong (pivot misalignment causes shoulder impingement); raising above shoulder height; using momentum; not adjusting the machine to the individual body proportions.',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['Pivot alignment: shoulder joint must match machine pivot','Shoulder height: stop at parallel every rep','Adjust the machine: seat height is critical','Dropsets: machines make dropsets easy — use this advantage'],
 array['Cable lateral raise for free range','Dumbbell lateral raise for natural path','Leaning lateral raise for extended range'],
 array['Band lateral raise','Manual resistance lateral raise','Resistance tube lateral raise'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','machine_lateral_raise','guided','beginner','dropset'], array['shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'frontal', false, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Barbell Overhead Press Narrow Stance (Strict)',
 'shoulder', array['triceps','upper_traps'], array['shoulder','triceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Standing barbell overhead press with strict form: feet shoulder-width, no leg drive, bar starts at upper chest/clavicle. Press directly overhead. At the top, the bar is directly over the center of mass (over the ears, not in front). Lower under control to clavicle. No leg drive = all deltoid, upper trap, and tricep. This is the strictest overhead press. Develops raw pressing strength and shoulder stability. If the elbows drift forward, the bar is too heavy — use leg drive (push press) or reduce weight.',
 'Using leg drive on a strict press (changes exercise intent); bar path going in front of the body instead of overhead; not locking out at the top; pressing with a severely flared elbow grip.',
 'shoulder_hypertrophy', array['Over the ears at the top: not in front of the head','Rib cage down: do not arch the lower back at lockout','No leg drive: feet are fixed, hips are fixed','Elbow angle: 30-45° in front — not like a bench press and not straight forward'],
 array['Push press for more weight','Jerk for maximal overhead loading','Seated strict press for even more strict form'],
 array['Dumbbell overhead press seated','Smith machine shoulder press','Landmine press (shoulder-friendly)'],
 array['bodybuilding','shoulder','overhead_press','strict','standing','barbell','strength'], array['shoulder_impingement','lower_back_pain'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 8, null, 120, true);

