('Incline Dumbbell Curl (Long Head Bicep)',
 'biceps', array['forearms'], array['biceps','forearms'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','incline_bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Set the incline bench to 45-60° (NOT 30 — too upright; the steeper the incline the more long head stretch). Sit back against the bench. Let the arms hang BEHIND the body due to the incline — this is the stretched position for the long head of the bicep. Curl from this stretched position to full contraction. Do NOT let the elbows drift forward as you curl (they must stay behind the torso plane). The stretch at the bottom is the key to this exercise. This is the premier bicep peak builder.',
 'Elbows drifting forward (losing the stretched position — makes it a standard curl); bench angle too shallow (reduces long head stretch); using momentum and swinging; not allowing the arms to hang fully at the bottom.',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['Elbows stay behind the body: do not let them drift forward','Full hang: feel the long head stretch at the bottom','45-60° bench: steeper than you think','Peak contraction: squeeze hard at the top'],
 array['Spider curl (even more stretch emphasis)','Incline dumbbell curl with supination','Weighted incline curl for maximum overload'],
 array['Standard standing dumbbell curl','Preacher curl (opposite — short head emphasis)','Resistance band curl seated'],
 array['bodybuilding','biceps','incline_curl','long_head','peak','stretch','dumbbell'], array['bicep_tendinopathy'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', true, 4, 10, null, 75, true),

('Spider Curl (Extreme Stretch Bicep Curl)',
 'biceps', array['forearms'], array['biceps','forearms'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','preacher_bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Stand behind a preacher bench and lean over the VERTICAL face (the face that angles toward you when you do a normal preacher curl). Let the arms hang straight down over the vertical pad. Curl from this position. The arms are directly vertical at the start, creating maximum long head stretch and constant tension through the full range. Both short and long heads are hit intensely. Also works with EZ bar on the preacher curl pad (using the vertical side). This is a brutal isolation curl for bicep thickness and peak.',
 'Using the angled face instead of the vertical face (reduces the stretch); swinging the elbows up off the pad; going too heavy (you will lose form immediately); not going all the way to full extension at the bottom.',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['Vertical face: the steep side of the preacher bench','Elbows stay on the pad: do not lift them','Full extension: allow arms to straighten completely','Feel the stretch: the bottom position is where the magic is'],
 array['Spider curl with barbell on vertical face','Cable spider curl from pulley below','Spider curl with added supination during curl'],
 array['Preacher curl standard (short head)','Standing dumbbell curl','Incline dumbbell curl (long head)'],
 array['bodybuilding','biceps','spider_curl','extreme_stretch','long_head','isolation'], array['elbow_tendinopathy','bicep_tendinopathy'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', true, 4, 12, null, 75, true),

('Preacher Curl EZ Bar',
 'biceps', array['forearms'], array['biceps','forearms'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['ez_bar','preacher_bench'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit at the preacher bench. Grip the inner angled portion of the EZ bar. Place the upper arm on the angled pad — the pad prevents the elbows from rising. Curl from full extension to full contraction. The preacher bench eliminates momentum and cheating because the arms are fixed against the pad. The EZ bar angle reduces wrist strain compared to a straight bar. This exercise strongly emphasizes the short head (inner) of the bicep, creating fullness and width. Use controlled reps.',
 'Leaning back and cheating at the top (the pad should prevent this — sit down); not reaching full extension at the bottom (partial reps cheat the stretch); dropping the elbows off the pad; using a grip that is too wide on the EZ bar.',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['Elbows stay on the pad: the entire point of the machine','Full extension: all the way down every rep','Short head emphasis: this is the width and fullness builder','EZ bar angle: more comfortable on the wrists than straight bar'],
 array['Preacher curl with dumbbell single arm','Heavy preacher curl for strength phase','Preacher curl with added pause at bottom stretch'],
 array['Standing barbell curl','Machine bicep curl','Resistance band curl'],
 array['bodybuilding','biceps','preacher_curl','ez_bar','short_head','width','isolation'], array['elbow_tendinopathy'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 10, null, 75, true),

('Hammer Curl (Brachialis Emphasis)',
 'biceps', array['forearms','brachioradialis'], array['biceps','forearms'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell'], 'beginner', false,
 'Hold dumbbells at the sides with a neutral grip (palms facing each other — like holding hammers). Curl both arms simultaneously OR alternating. The neutral grip shifts emphasis from the biceps brachii to the brachialis (the muscle beneath the bicep) and brachioradialis (forearm). Building the brachialis pushes the bicep up, creating the illusion of a larger, higher bicep peak. Also excellent for forearm strength. Keep elbows at the sides and do not allow them to drift forward.',
 'Supinating the wrist (turning it into a standard curl — defeating the neutral grip purpose); elbows drifting forward at the top; using too much weight and swinging; not keeping the thumb up position throughout.',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['Thumbs up: neutral grip maintained throughout the full range','Elbows back: stay at the sides, do not swing forward','Alternating version: better mind-muscle with lighter weight','Brachialis builder: different from bicep — train both'],
 array['Cross-body hammer curl (more brachioradialis)','Rope hammer curl on cable','Incline hammer curl for stretch emphasis'],
 array['Standard dumbbell curl','Band bicep curl','Machine curl neutral grip'],
 array['bodybuilding','biceps','hammer_curl','brachialis','brachioradialis','neutral_grip'], array['wrist_injury'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', true, 4, 12, null, 60, true),

('Skull Crusher (Lying Tricep Extension)',
 'triceps', array['forearms'], array['triceps','forearms'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['ez_bar','barbell','bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Lie on a flat bench. Hold an EZ bar (or barbell) with a close grip, arms extended above the chest. Lower the bar toward the forehead (hence "skull crusher") by bending ONLY at the elbows — upper arms remain vertical and stationary. Lower until the bar nearly touches the forehead or goes slightly behind the head for more range. Press back to start. The EZ bar is preferred for wrist comfort. All three tricep heads are targeted, with long head emphasis at the stretched position.',
 'Moving the upper arms (turning it into a decline press — they must stay vertical); not going to full range at the bottom; elbows flaring wide; using a straight bar when wrists protest (use EZ bar instead).',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['Upper arms vertical: they do not move — only the forearms','Bar toward forehead: or slightly behind for more stretch','Elbows track straight: do not flare them wide','EZ bar preferred: straight bar causes wrist strain for most'],
 array['Dumbbell skull crusher (independent arms)','Decline skull crusher for more range','Cable skull crusher for constant tension'],
 array['Rope pushdown','Overhead cable extension','Dumbbell overhead tricep extension'],
 array['bodybuilding','triceps','skull_crusher','lying_extension','all_heads','ez_bar'], array['elbow_tendinopathy'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 10, null, 90, true),

('Overhead Rope Tricep Extension',
 'triceps', array[], array['triceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine','rope_attachment'], 'beginner', false,
 'Cable pulley set low or at floor. Attach rope. Face away from the cable (or can face the cable). Grip rope overhead with both hands (palms facing each other). Extend the arms overhead, separating the rope at the top for full range. The overhead position fully stretches the long head of the tricep (the largest head), which is a unique advantage over pushdowns. The long head crosses the shoulder joint — it must be stretched to be fully recruited. This is the best isolation exercise for tricep mass.',
 'Elbows flaring wide (reduces long head involvement); not separating the rope at the top (loses the final degrees of range); letting the elbows come forward during the movement; using momentum.',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['Overhead position: fully stretches the long head — critical for size','Elbows at ears: keep them pointed straight up','Separate the rope at the top: maximize range','Long head is the largest head: overhead work is mass work'],
 array['Dumbbell overhead tricep extension standing','Barbell overhead tricep extension','Single-arm overhead cable extension'],
 array['Rope pushdown (shorter range)','Bench dip bodyweight','Tricep kickback'],
 array['bodybuilding','triceps','overhead_extension','rope','long_head','cable','mass'], array['elbow_tendinopathy','shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Close-Grip Bench Press',
 'triceps', array['chest','shoulder'], array['triceps','chest','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','bench'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Grip the barbell with hands 15-20 cm apart (NOT narrower — too narrow causes wrist pain and reduces force output). Lower the bar to the lower chest while keeping elbows TUCKED in (30° from the body). Press back up. The close grip shifts more demand to the triceps than the pectorals compared to a standard bench press. This is a mass-building compound movement for the triceps. Can be loaded heavier than most isolation tricep exercises. Essential for powerlifters and bodybuilders alike.',
 'Gripping too narrow (inside 15 cm — wrist strain and no advantage); allowing elbows to flare wide (converts to a chest exercise); bouncing the bar off the chest; not taking the triceps to full extension at the top.',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['15-20 cm grip: not hands touching — that is too narrow','Elbows tucked 30°: halfway between full flare and fully tucked','Lower chest touch: not sternum area','Full lockout: triceps fully contracted at the top'],
 array['Close-grip bench press with chains','Close-grip board press','Close-grip bench as main lift for tricep strength'],
 array['Tricep pushdown rope','Close-grip pushup (bodyweight)','Machine chest press narrow grip'],
 array['bodybuilding','triceps','close_grip_bench','compound','strength','mass'], array['wrist_injury','shoulder_impingement'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 8, null, 120, true),

('Tricep Pushdown – Straight Bar vs Rope vs V-Bar',
 'triceps', array[], array['triceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine'], 'beginner', false,
 'Cable pulley at top. Three variations with different emphasis: (1) Straight bar — overhand grip, both heads symmetrically; (2) Rope — neutral grip, allows full supination at the bottom (separate the rope to open the lateral head fully); (3) V-bar — similar to straight bar with a slight wrist angle. Stand close to the cable. Keep upper arms pinned to the sides. Push down through full extension, squeeze at the bottom. Return under control — do not let the cable jerk the arms back up. The rope allows the most range of motion.',
 'Elbows drifting forward (they must stay pinned to the sides — no forward drift); using the body weight to push the cable down (core must stay upright); partial reps at the top; bending at the waist.',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['Elbows pinned: upper arms do not move — only the forearms','Stand close: leaning too far back changes the leverage','Rope split: at the bottom, spread the rope for full extension','Feel the squeeze: hold 1 second at full extension'],
 array['Single-arm cable pushdown for unilateral work','Reverse-grip pushdown for lateral head','Pushdown with pause at bottom contraction'],
 array['Bench dip bodyweight','Resistance band pushdown','Overhead tricep extension'],
 array['bodybuilding','triceps','pushdown','cable','variation','beginner','isolation'], array['elbow_tendinopathy'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Tricep Kickback (Dumbbell)',
 'triceps', array[], array['triceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell'], 'beginner', false,
 'Hinge forward to near-parallel. Support with non-working hand on a bench. Upper arm parallel to the floor, elbow bent at 90°. Extend the forearm back and up until the arm is fully straight and parallel to the floor. Squeeze the tricep at full extension. Return under control. Effective for lateral head isolation when the upper arm is held parallel — the contraction is maximal when the arm is straight and horizontal. Use light weight; heavy kickbacks never look right.',
 'Upper arm not parallel to the floor (reduces the range where the tricep is fully contracted); swinging the arm back using momentum; not reaching full extension at the end; heavy weight that makes form impossible.',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['Upper arm parallel: this is the fixed position — it does not move','Full extension: the squeeze only happens when fully straight','Light weight: this is a finishing isolation exercise','Feel the lateral head: outer tricep contracting'],
 array['Cable kickback (constant tension version)','Bilateral kickback with bench support','Single-arm cable kickback from low pulley'],
 array['Pushdown (easier to load)','Band kickback','Machine tricep extension'],
 array['bodybuilding','triceps','kickback','dumbbell','lateral_head','finishing','isolation'], array['elbow_tendinopathy'],
 'push', 'sagittal', true, 3, 15, null, 60, true),

('EZ Bar Concentration Curl (Seated)',
 'biceps', array['forearms'], array['biceps','forearms'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['ez_bar','bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Sit at the end of a flat bench. Lean forward slightly. Hold the EZ bar with an underhand grip, elbows resting on the inner thighs. Curl the bar toward the chest. The elbow-on-thigh position completely eliminates swinging and cheating — the movement is purely the bicep. Full extension at the bottom, full supination at the top. The position emphasizes the short head and creates a powerful peak contraction. Excellent as a final isolation exercise at the end of a bicep session.',
 'Not resting the elbows firmly on the thighs (allows cheating); not reaching full extension at the bottom; wrist bending backward at the top (maintain a flat or slightly supinated wrist); rushing.',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['Elbows on inner thighs: this is the cheat-eliminator','Full extension: arms straight at the bottom every rep','Supinate at the top: palms rotate toward the ceiling','This is the peak builder: short head, inner bicep'],
 array['Dumbbell concentration curl one arm','Preacher curl for similar short-head emphasis','Cable concentration curl'],
 array['Standard standing curl','Machine curl seated','Resistance band curl'],
 array['bodybuilding','biceps','concentration_curl','ez_bar','short_head','isolation','seated'], array['elbow_tendinopathy'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 3, 12, null, 60, true),

('21s Bicep Curl Protocol',
 'biceps', array['forearms'], array['biceps','forearms'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','ez_bar'], 'intermediate', false,
 '21s consist of three phases of 7 reps each: (1) Lower 7 reps — from the bottom of the curl to the halfway point (90°); (2) Upper 7 reps — from 90° to full contraction at the top; (3) Full 7 reps — full range from bottom to top. The total of 21 reps creates a pump and metabolic stress far beyond standard curls. The partials in the bottom and top thirds emphasize different portions of the strength curve. Use approximately 60% of normal curl weight. Do not rest between the three phases.',
 'Stopping mid-set to rest (the three phases must be done consecutively without rest); using full weight (use 60% or less); not properly dividing the range into true thirds; rushing the reps to get through the set.',
 'arms_hypertrophy', array['Three phases no rest: lower half, upper half, full range — continuous','60% weight: this will feel heavy by the third phase','Count carefully: 7 + 7 + 7 = 21 total','Pump: expect significant bicep pump from this protocol'],
 array['Cable 21s for constant tension','Dumbbell 21s alternating arms','21s superset with heavy standard curls'],
 array['Standard barbell curl','Machine curl','Resistance band curl'],
 array['bodybuilding','biceps','21s','protocol','pump','metabolic','advanced_technique'], array['elbow_tendinopathy'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 3, null, null, 90, true);

-- ─── SECTION 5: LEGS SPECIALIZATION (QUAD / HAMSTRING / GLUTE / CALF) ────────
insert into exercises (name, primary_muscle_group, secondary_muscle_groups, muscle_groups, category, movement_type, equipment, difficulty_level, is_compound, instructions, common_mistakes, subcategory, coaching_cues, progressions, regressions, tags, contraindications, force_type, plane_of_motion, is_unilateral, sets_default, reps_default, duration_seconds, rest_seconds, is_system) values

('Leg Extension Machine (Quad Isolation)',
 'quadriceps', array[], array['quadriceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['leg_extension_machine'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit in the leg extension machine. Adjust the seat so the knee joint aligns with the machine pivot. Adjust the shin pad to sit just above the ankle. Extend both legs until fully straight. Squeeze the quads at full extension for 1-2 seconds. Lower slowly — the eccentric is where most muscle damage occurs. The leg extension is the only true quad isolation exercise. Use for pre-exhaust (before squats), as a finisher, or for rehabilitation purposes where compound loading is not appropriate.',
 'Seat position wrong (knee joint not aligned with pivot — this creates joint shear forces); slamming the weight down; not reaching full extension; using momentum to kick the weight up.',
 'legs_hypertrophy', array['Knee-to-pivot alignment: adjust before starting','Full extension: squeeze the quads hard at the top','Slow eccentric: 3-4 count lowering','Pre-exhaust or finish: use before squats for greater quad activation or after squats as a burnout'],
 array['Single-leg extension for imbalance correction','Leg extension with pause at full contraction','Leg extension dropset — reduce weight without rest'],
 array['Bodyweight quad extension (lying quad contraction)','Resistance band terminal knee extension','Isometric quad set'],
 array['bodybuilding','quadriceps','leg_extension','isolation','machine','quad_only'], array['knee_osteoarthritis','patella_tendinopathy'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 15, null, 60, true),

('Lying Leg Curl (Hamstring Isolation)',
 'hamstrings', array['glutes','calves'], array['hamstrings','glutes'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['lying_leg_curl_machine'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie prone on the leg curl machine. Adjust the leg pad to sit just above the Achilles, with the knee joint at the edge of the pad. Curl the legs toward the glutes. At the top, the feet should approach or touch the glutes. Hold 1-2 seconds. Lower slowly. Plantarflexing (pointing the feet) at the top shortens the gastrocnemius and reduces its contribution, making this more strictly a hamstring exercise. The prone position allows full hip extension, maximizing the stretch on the hamstrings.',
 'Not adjusting the machine for body proportions; not going to full contraction (just halfway up); releasing the weight quickly without controlling the eccentric; hips rising off the pad at the top.',
 'legs_hypertrophy', array['Hips on the pad: they must not rise as you curl','Full range: feet toward glutes at the top','Slow eccentric: 3-4 count lowering is where growth happens','Plantarflex for strict hamstring: point the toes to reduce gastrocnemius'],
 array['Single-leg curl for imbalance correction','Seated leg curl (different angle of pull)','Nordic hamstring curl (eccentric only)'],
 array['Resistance band hamstring curl lying','Stability ball hamstring curl','Glute bridge (hip extension pattern)'],
 array['bodybuilding','hamstrings','lying_leg_curl','isolation','machine','prone'], array['hamstring_tear','knee_injury'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 12, null, 75, true),

('Seated Leg Curl Machine',
 'hamstrings', array['glutes'], array['hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['seated_leg_curl_machine'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit in the seated leg curl machine with thighs supported on the pad. The shin pad rests just above the ankle. Curl the legs downward and back under the seat. In the seated position, the hips are at 90° flexion, which PRE-STRETCHES the hamstrings through the hip — creating more range at the knee joint than the lying version. This is biomechanically advantageous for hamstring recruitment. The seated position also makes it easier to maintain stability. Many coaches prefer seated over lying for this reason.',
 'Not adjusting the thigh pad (should lock the thighs firmly against the pad); not completing the full range of motion; releasing the weight at the bottom; the machine not fitting the body size.',
 'legs_hypertrophy', array['Thigh pad locks down: if thighs rise, the machine is wrong for you','Seated stretches more: the hip flexion pre-stretches the hamstring','Full range: down until machine stops, not until you stop','Slow return: control the eccentric as the legs extend'],
 array['Single-arm seated leg curl','Seated leg curl with pause at full contraction','Heavier seated curl after mastering the machine'],
 array['Lying leg curl','Resistance band hamstring curl','Stability ball hamstring curl'],
 array['bodybuilding','hamstrings','seated_leg_curl','machine','hip_flexion','stretch'], array['hamstring_tear'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 12, null, 75, true),

('Hack Squat Machine (Quad-Dominant)',
 'quadriceps', array['glutes','hamstrings'], array['quadriceps','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['hack_squat_machine'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Position feet shoulder-width on the platform, low and forward (emphasizes quads over glutes). Shoulders against the pads. Unhook the safety handles. Lower under control until knees are at 90° or deeper. Press back up through the entire foot. The hack squat machine allows a more upright torso than a barbell squat, which shifts emphasis to the quads. The fixed path also eliminates balance requirements, allowing you to focus purely on the quads. Excellent machine for quad hypertrophy.',
 'Feet too high and wide (turns into a glute machine, not quad machine); allowing knees to cave; not going to at least 90°; locking out the knees aggressively at the top (keep tension).',
 'legs_hypertrophy', array['Low feet: quad emphasis — the lower the feet, the more quad','Knees track over toes: always','90° minimum: go deeper if knees are healthy','Do not lock out: keep tension on the quads at the top'],
 array['Hack squat with narrow stance for extreme VMO emphasis','V-Squat machine variation','Combine hack squat with leg press on same leg day'],
 array['Leg press machine','Goblet squat bodyweight','Smith machine squat'],
 array['bodybuilding','quadriceps','hack_squat','machine','compound','quad_dominant'], array['knee_osteoarthritis','patella_tendinopathy'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 10, null, 120, true),

('Bulgarian Split Squat (Rear Foot Elevated)',
 'quadriceps', array['glutes','hamstrings'], array['quadriceps','glutes'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','bench'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Rear foot elevated on a bench (the instep, not the toes — for comfort). Front foot far enough forward that the shin is vertical at the bottom of the movement. Hold dumbbells or a barbell. Lower the rear knee toward the floor. The front knee tracks over the toes. Rise by pressing through the front heel. This is perhaps the most effective unilateral leg exercise for hypertrophy, correcting left-right imbalances, and building functional strength. The elevated rear foot increases range of motion compared to a standard split squat.',
 'Rear foot too close to the bench (front shin angles forward, creating excessive knee stress); not going deep enough; front knee caving; using a barbell before mastering the dumbbell version.',
 'legs_hypertrophy', array['Shin vertical at the bottom: foot position determines this','Hip drop straight down: not forward — the rear foot does the job','Front knee over toes: tracking follows the foot','Rear foot instep: do not put toes on the bench — use the instep'],
 array['Barbell Bulgarian split squat (heavier loading)','Bulgarian split squat with pause at the bottom','Add bands for accommodating resistance'],
 array['Standard split squat (rear foot flat)','Reverse lunge','Assisted split squat with TRX'],
 array['bodybuilding','quadriceps','bulgarian_split_squat','unilateral','glute','hypertrophy'], array['knee_injury','hip_flexor_strain'],
 'push', 'sagittal', true, 4, 10, null, 90, true),

('Hip Thrust (Barbell Glute Bridge)',
 'glutes', array['hamstrings','core'], array['glutes','hamstrings'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','bench'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Sit on the floor with the upper back against a bench. Bar across the hips (use a pad for comfort). Feet flat on the floor, shoulder-width. Drive through the heels to lift the hips to full extension — creating a straight line from knees to shoulders. Squeeze the glutes MAXIMALLY at the top. Lower under control. This is the premier glute isolation exercise, providing the highest levels of glute activation of any exercise. The loaded hip thrust is fundamental to glute hypertrophy training.',
 'Not reaching full hip extension at the top; lower back hyperextending at the top (the back should not arch — just the hips drive up); feet too close (hamstrings dominate) or too far (back dominates); not using a pad (leads to stopping sets early due to bar discomfort).',
 'legs_hypertrophy', array['Full hip extension: hips drive to the ceiling — maximum height','Glutes squeeze: at the top, actively contract the glutes as hard as possible','Ribs down: do not arch the back — it is just the hips elevating','Foot position: test different widths to find what you feel most in glutes'],
 array['Banded barbell hip thrust for extra glute activation','Single-leg hip thrust for unilateral work','Heavy barbell hip thrust for strength and mass'],
 array['Bodyweight glute bridge (on the floor)','Feet-elevated glute bridge','Resistance band glute bridge'],
 array['bodybuilding','glutes','hip_thrust','barbell','glute_bridge','isolation','strength'], array['lower_back_pain'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 12, null, 90, true),

('Standing Calf Raise Machine (Gastrocnemius)',
 'calves', array[], array['calves'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['calf_raise_machine'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand on the platform of a calf raise machine, the ball of the foot on the edge, heel hanging freely. Shoulders under the pads. Full range of motion: lower the heel as far below the step as possible (full dorsiflexion stretch) then rise to the highest possible point (maximum plantarflexion). Hold the peak contraction for 2 seconds. The gastrocnemius is a two-joint muscle (crosses the knee and ankle) — it is best trained with the knee straight (standing position). Calves respond well to high reps and long time under tension.',
 'Not going through full range of motion (partial reps are very common in calf training — they limit growth); bouncing at the bottom (using elasticity instead of muscle); not holding the peak contraction; going too heavy at the expense of range.',
 'legs_hypertrophy', array['Full range: maximum stretch at bottom, maximum height at top','2-second hold at top: calves need peak contraction time','Knee straight: for gastrocnemius, do not bend the knee','High reps: calves are high-fatigue-resistant — 15-25 reps are effective'],
 array['Single-leg calf raise (one-legged for double the load)','Weighted standing calf raise with heavier loading','Donkey calf raise (hips flexed — different stimulus)'],
 array['Seated calf raise (soleus emphasis)','Bodyweight calf raise on a step','Resistance band plantarflexion'],
 array['bodybuilding','calves','calf_raise','standing','gastrocnemius','isolation'], array['achilles_tendinopathy'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 20, null, 60, true),

('Seated Calf Raise (Soleus Emphasis)',
 'calves', array[], array['calves'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['seated_calf_raise_machine'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit at a seated calf raise machine. The pads sit on the lower thighs, just above the knee. Feet on the platform, heels free. Lower to full dorsiflexion then plantarflex maximally. Hold 2 seconds. Because the knee is BENT at 90°, the gastrocnemius is slackened at the knee — this removes its contribution and places all stress on the soleus. The soleus is the deeper, larger calf muscle that contributes to calf size and thickness more than the gastrocnemius. Many bodybuilders neglect this exercise.',
 'Not actually using a seated calf raise machine (barbell on knees does not replicate the same force angle well); not going through full range; not holding at the top; rushing through the set.',
 'legs_hypertrophy', array['Knee bent: this is what isolates the soleus from the gastrocnemius','Full range: same principle as standing — go all the way down','2-second peak: hold at the top for the soleus to work hard','The soleus builds calf SIZE: do not skip this for the standing version alone'],
 array['Single-leg seated calf raise','Heavier seated calf raise as a strength lift','Seated calf raise with longer pauses (3 seconds)'],
 array['Standing calf raise (gastrocnemius)','Bodyweight seated calf raise','Resistance band seated plantarflexion'],
 array['bodybuilding','calves','seated_calf_raise','soleus','knee_bent','isolation'], array['achilles_tendinopathy'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 20, null, 60, true),

('Glute-Ham Raise (GHR)',
 'hamstrings', array['glutes','calves'], array['hamstrings','glutes'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['ghr_machine'], 'advanced', false,
 'Kneel on the glute-ham developer with ankles secured. Body upright initially. Lower the torso toward the floor by controlling the eccentric at the knee — the hamstrings eccentrically work as you lower. At the bottom, press back up using the hamstrings (knee flexion) to return to upright. This is one of the few exercises that works the hamstrings as both a knee flexor AND a hip extensor simultaneously. Extremely challenging. Many cannot perform a single full rep initially — use band assistance.',
 'Initiating the movement from the hips (it should be knee flexion first, not a back extension); dropping too fast with no eccentric control; not using band assistance when needed; hyperextending the lower back at the top.',
 'legs_hypertrophy', array['Hamstrings drive: knee flexion brings you back up — not the back','Eccentric control: resist the lowering — do not fall forward','Band assist: if you cannot do one rep, use a band for assistance','Hip extension at top: finish with glutes at the lockout'],
 array['Weighted GHR (holding a plate on the chest)','GHR without assistance for advanced athletes','Nordic hamstring curl (similar but different machine)'],
 array['Assisted GHR with band','Nordic curl regression','Prone hamstring curl machine'],
 array['bodybuilding','hamstrings','ghr','glute_ham_raise','advanced','knee_flexion','eccentric'], array['hamstring_tear','knee_injury'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 3, 8, null, 120, true),

('Leg Press (Quad Emphasis – Low Foot Placement)',
 'quadriceps', array['glutes','hamstrings'], array['quadriceps','glutes'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['leg_press_machine'], 'beginner', true,
 'Sit in the leg press. Place feet LOW on the platform (below center) and shoulder-width. Lower the weight by bending the knees until 90° (or below if using full range for hypertrophy — without the lower back rounding). Press back up through the full foot — do not allow the knees to lock out. Low foot placement decreases hip flexion involvement and increases quad demand. The leg press is excellent for very heavy loading without the spinal compression of a barbell squat, making it ideal for volume work.',
 'Knees collapsing inward; locking out completely at the top (removes tension from quads — keep a slight bend); lower back peeling off the seat (severe disc injury risk — do not go deeper than your flexibility allows); feet too high and wide (turns into a glute exercise).',
 'legs_hypertrophy', array['Low feet: quad machine — glutes minimal','No lockout: keep tension — slight bend at the top','Back flat: if lower back rounds, the range is too deep','Press through the full foot: not just the heels or toes'],
 array['Narrow stance leg press for VMO emphasis','Single-leg press for unilateral work','Extremely heavy leg press for strength'],
 array['Goblet squat bodyweight','Assisted squat machine (Smith)','Leg extension machine'],
 array['bodybuilding','quadriceps','leg_press','machine','low_foot','quad_emphasis'], array['knee_osteoarthritis','lower_back_disc'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 12, null, 120, true);

-- ─── SECTION 6: HYPERTROPHY TECHNIQUES & ADVANCED METHODS ────────────────────
insert into exercises (name, primary_muscle_group, secondary_muscle_groups, muscle_groups, category, movement_type, equipment, difficulty_level, is_compound, instructions, common_mistakes, subcategory, coaching_cues, progressions, regressions, tags, contraindications, force_type, plane_of_motion, is_unilateral, sets_default, reps_default, duration_seconds, rest_seconds, is_system) values

('Drop Set Protocol (Descending Weight Method)',
 'chest', array['triceps','shoulder'], array['chest','triceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['dumbbell','cable_machine'], 'intermediate', false,
 'A drop set: perform a set to failure (or near failure), then immediately reduce the weight by 20-30% and continue for more reps without rest. Repeat 2-4 times. Example: dumbbell press — 30 kg × 10, drop to 22 kg × 8, drop to 16 kg × 8. The drop set prolongs time under tension past normal failure, recruiting additional motor units and creating greater metabolic stress. Most effective on machine or cable exercises (quick weight changes). Best used as the LAST set of an exercise.',
 'Starting with too heavy a weight (the drops become uncontrollable); resting between drops (must be immediate); using drop sets for every set of every exercise (excessive — use sparingly, last set only); dropping too much weight (30% max per drop for most exercises).',
 'hypertrophy_technique', array['Last set: drop sets on the final set only — not every set','Immediate: no rest between drops — rack, reduce, continue','20-30% drop: not too much, not too little','Machine/cable first: easier to execute drop sets quickly'],
 array['Triple drop set (three consecutive drops)','Strip set on barbell (remove plates each drop)','Rest-pause plus drop set for maximum intensity'],
 array['Standard straight sets','Two-rep drop set (one drop only)','Assisted last rep forced reps'],
 array['bodybuilding','hypertrophy_technique','drop_set','descending','metabolic','advanced'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 1, null, null, 120, true),

('Rest-Pause Training (Myo-Rep Method)',
 'back', array['biceps'], array['back','biceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['cable_machine','dumbbell'], 'advanced', false,
 'Rest-pause: perform a set to failure. Rest 10-20 seconds (partial recovery). Perform more reps (until failure again). Rest 10-20 seconds. Continue for 2-4 mini-sets. Example: cable row — 12 reps to failure, rest 15s, 4 reps, rest 15s, 3 reps, rest 15s, 2 reps. Total reps: 21. The brief rest allows enough ATP recovery to squeeze out more high-quality reps without fully recovering. Myo-reps (the final mini-sets) are extremely effective for hypertrophy due to high motor unit recruitment at fatigue.',
 'Resting too long between mini-sets (defeats the purpose — keep it 10-20 seconds); using with exercises where failure is dangerous (do not rest-pause on squats or bench without spotters); applying to every exercise every session.',
 'hypertrophy_technique', array['15-second rest: shorter than you think — set a timer','Mini-sets: 2-5 reps per mini-set is normal','Safe exercises only: cables and machines are ideal, not free-weight squats','Last set of the day: use for the final set of an exercise to finish'],
 array['Myo-rep match protocol (match the activation set volume across sessions)','Rest-pause with decreasing rest intervals','Cluster sets (structured rest-pause for strength)'],
 array['Standard sets to failure','Forced reps with a spotter','Drop sets (different method, similar principle)'],
 array['bodybuilding','hypertrophy_technique','rest_pause','myo_reps','motor_unit','advanced'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 1, null, null, 120, true),

('Occlusion Training (Blood Flow Restriction – BFR)',
 'quadriceps', array[], array['quadriceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['bfr_cuffs','resistance_band'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Blood flow restriction: apply a cuff or band to the upper portion of the limb (upper thigh for legs, upper arm for arms) at 60-80% occlusion pressure. Perform high-rep sets (15-30 reps) with very light loads (20-30% of 1RM). The partial venous occlusion creates metabolic stress and cellular swelling that signals hypertrophy without heavy loads. Evidence: BFR at 20-30% 1RM produces similar hypertrophy to conventional training at 70-80% 1RM. Particularly valuable for injured athletes, post-surgical recovery, and those who cannot tolerate heavy loads.',
 'Occluding arteries completely (very dangerous — the cuff should restrict venous return, not arterial inflow; the limb should still be warm and blood should enter); training to 100% failure under BFR (not recommended — the metabolic stress is extreme); using extremely narrow bands (width matters — use 3-5 cm minimum for safety).',
 'hypertrophy_technique', array['60-80% venous occlusion: not 100%','20-30% of 1RM: go light — the restriction does the work','High reps: 15-30 reps per set','Warm sensation: limb should feel pumped and warm — if cold or numb, release immediately'],
 array['BFR walking for lower body (very light stimulus)','BFR with bodyweight exercises for complete beginners','Advanced BFR with moderate loads'],
 array['Standard light weight training','Machine-based exercises without restriction','Physical therapy baseline exercises'],
 array['bodybuilding','hypertrophy_technique','bfr','occlusion','blood_flow_restriction','rehabilitation'], array['cardiovascular_disease','hypertension','deep_vein_thrombosis'],
 'isometric', 'multi', false, 4, 25, null, 45, true),

('Mechanical Drop Set (Weaker to Stronger Grip)',
 'back', array['biceps'], array['back','biceps'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['pullup_bar'], 'advanced', false,
 'Mechanical drop set: instead of reducing weight, change the exercise to a mechanically easier variation. Example for back: (1) Pronated wide-grip pullup to failure → immediately (2) Neutral-grip pullup to failure → immediately (3) Chin-up (supinated) to failure. Each position is stronger, allowing more reps without rest. The lats are exhausted through all three positions. Works extremely well for pullups, rows, and pressing variations. No weight changes needed — just change grip or position.',
 'Resting between variations (must be immediate transitions); choosing the wrong order (start with the hardest position and move to easier); applying this to exercises where position changes take too long.',
 'hypertrophy_technique', array['Hardest first: always start with the most challenging variant','Immediate transition: change grip without rest','Failure each variation: go until you cannot perform another controlled rep','Pullups are ideal: easy to change grip without equipment changes'],
 array['Mechanical drop set with added weight at the start','Three-level mechanical drop for maximum volume','Mechanical drop superset with cable rows'],
 array['Standard drop set (weight reduction)','Forced reps with spotter','Rest-pause method'],
 array['bodybuilding','hypertrophy_technique','mechanical_drop_set','grip_variation','advanced','pullup'], array[],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, null, 120, true),

('Supersets: Agonist-Antagonist',
 'chest', array['back','triceps','biceps'], array['chest','back'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','cable_machine'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Agonist-antagonist superset: pair exercises that work opposing muscle groups, performed back-to-back with no rest between them. Classic pairs: chest press + row (chest/back); bicep curl + tricep extension; leg extension + leg curl; shoulder press + face pull. Benefits: (1) Enhanced neural drive — working the antagonist briefly enhances agonist strength on the next exercise; (2) Time efficiency — both muscles trained in the time of one. Rest 60-90 seconds between supersets. Total volume equals two separate exercises in half the time.',
 'Pairing exercises that are too fatiguing (both exhausting compound lifts are harder to pair than a compound with an isolation); resting between the two exercises (defeat the time advantage); choosing exercises at opposite ends of the gym (transition time reduces effectiveness).',
 'hypertrophy_technique', array['Antagonist enhances agonist: this is evidence-based — your row improves your bench press performance','No rest between the two: the rest comes after both are done','Adjacent equipment: set up both exercises before starting','Time efficient: the same volume in half the time'],
 array['Triple superset (three opposing muscle groups)','Giant set with four antagonist exercises','Superset with increasing weight each round'],
 array['Standard straight sets','Circuit training with rest','Single exercise focus'],
 array['bodybuilding','hypertrophy_technique','superset','agonist_antagonist','time_efficient','paired'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 4, 12, null, 90, true),

('Time Under Tension (TUT) Tempo Training',
 'quadriceps', array['glutes','hamstrings'], array['quadriceps','glutes'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','dumbbell'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Tempo training specifies the speed of each phase of a lift: written as a four-number code (e.g., 4-1-2-0). First number: eccentric (lowering) seconds. Second: pause at the bottom. Third: concentric (lifting) seconds. Fourth: pause at the top. Example squat at 4-1-2-0: lower for 4 seconds, pause 1 second at the bottom, press up for 2 seconds, no pause at the top. TUT increases metabolic stress and creates greater muscle damage with lighter loads. A 6-second TUT rep recruits more type I fibers than a 2-second rep. Useful for hypertrophy blocks.',
 'Using too much weight with a slow tempo (form breaks down immediately); not actually counting the tempo (lifting at a normal tempo while claiming to use tempo); using slow tempo for strength work (slow tempos are for hypertrophy — not for 1RM attempts).',
 'hypertrophy_technique', array['Count aloud or use a metronome: the tempo must be accurate','Lighter weight: 60-70% of your normal weight for the same rep count','Eccentric is key: the 4-second lowering creates the most damage','TUT calculation: 6-10 seconds per rep = hypertrophy sweet spot'],
 array['Extended tempo 6-2-3-1 for maximum time under tension','Paused variations with longer holds','Super slow (10-second rep) for advanced metabolic stress'],
 array['Standard tempo lifting','Machine exercises with guided movement','Bodyweight exercises with natural tempo'],
 array['bodybuilding','hypertrophy_technique','tempo_training','tut','time_under_tension','eccentric'], array[],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 4, 8, null, 90, true);

