('Peak Week Depletion Protocol',
 'quadriceps', array['glutes','hamstrings','chest','back'], array['quadriceps','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'functional', 'other', array['barbell','dumbbell','cable_machine'], 'advanced', false,
 'Peak week — the final week before competition — typically involves a glycogen depletion protocol followed by a carb-loading phase. Depletion workout: high volume, full body, moderate weight, minimal rest (60 seconds) to deplete muscle glycogen stores. Example: 3-4 sets × 20-25 reps for every major muscle group. This is followed by 2-3 days of very low carbohydrate, then 1-2 days of carb-loading to fill out. Timing varies per individual. NOTE: Peak week protocols are highly individual and should only be done under experienced guidance.',
 'Trying a peak week protocol for the first time the week of competition (NEVER experiment in peak week — only use strategies tested in practice); doing too much volume in the depletion workout and creating fatigue; over-loading carbs (smooth look rather than full); making dietary mistakes during depletion.',
 'competition_prep', array['High rep depletion: 20-25 reps per set with minimal rest','Full body: every muscle group must be depleted','Never experiment: only use a protocol you have practiced before','Experienced guidance: this requires a competition coach'],
 array['Full competition simulation (depletion plus load plus show)','Contest prep coaching program','Advanced carb cycling protocol'],
 array['Standard cut with simple caloric deficit','Non-competition fat loss program','Recomposition training (no competition timeline)'],
 array['bodybuilding','competition','peak_week','depletion','glycogen','advanced'], array['eating_disorder','diabetes'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 4, 25, null, 60, true),

('Vacuum Pose (Transverse Abdominis)',
 'core', array[], array['core'],
 'functional', 'other', array['bodyweight'], 'intermediate', false,
 'The vacuum pose was the signature of classic bodybuilders (Arnold, Frank Zane, Robby Robinson). Stand upright, exhale all air from the lungs, then draw the navel in and up as far as possible. The transverse abdominis contracts isometrically. Hold 20-60 seconds while continuing to breathe shallowly. Practice daily (morning, on an empty stomach). The vacuum dramatically reduces waist size in photos and on stage. It also strengthens the TVA (transverse abdominis), which improves core stability and reduces low back pain.',
 'Exhaling too early and losing the vacuum (must hold through shallow breaths); not practicing regularly enough (like posing — requires daily conditioning); holding breath completely rather than shallow breathing during the hold.',
 'competition_prep', array['Full exhale first: empty the lungs before drawing in','Draw UP and IN: not just suck the stomach in','Shallow breath: breathe lightly to maintain the vacuum','Daily: morning on an empty stomach is the classic practice time'],
 array['Vacuum pose while posing routine','Extended vacuum hold 60+ seconds','Kneeling vacuum for deeper TVA activation'],
 array['Abdominal bracing practice','Diaphragmatic breathing exercises','Basic core hollowing exercise'],
 array['bodybuilding','competition','vacuum_pose','transverse_abdominis','classic_bodybuilding','waist'], array['hernia','diastasis_recti'],
 'isometric', 'transverse', false, 5, null, 20, 30, true),

('Off-Season Bulking Program Design',
 'chest', array['back','shoulder','quadriceps','biceps','triceps'], array['chest','back','shoulder'],
 'strength', 'strength', array['barbell','dumbbell','cable_machine'], 'advanced', true,
 'Off-season bulking focuses on progressive overload and caloric surplus to maximize muscle growth. Program structure: 4-6 days per week, body part split or push/pull/legs. Rep ranges: 6-12 for hypertrophy, with some strength work (3-6 reps) and metabolic work (15-25 reps). Weekly progression: increase load 2.5-5 kg on compound lifts when rep goal is achieved. Caloric surplus: 300-500 kcal above maintenance (lean bulk). Track body weight weekly — target 0.25-0.5 kg/week gain. If gaining faster, reduce calories slightly.',
 'Dirty bulking (excessive caloric surplus leads to unnecessary fat gain that is harder to lose later); no progressive overload tracking (random training produces random results); ignoring conditioning during the off-season (deconditioning affects health and the ability to diet); insufficient protein (2.0-2.4 g/kg is the evidence-based range).',
 'competition_prep', array['Track everything: log every set, rep, and weight','0.5 kg/week maximum: faster gain is mostly fat','2.0-2.4 g/kg protein: evidence-based for muscle gain','Progressive overload: if not getting stronger over months, the bulk is not working'],
 array['Advanced block periodization for off-season','Conjugate method for off-season powerbuilding','Periodized off-season with peaking block at end'],
 array['Basic beginner program (not an off-season specialist program)','Maintenance training (not a mass building phase)','Cut phase program (opposite goal)'],
 array['bodybuilding','competition','off_season','bulking','progressive_overload','program_design'], array[],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 4, 10, null, 90, true),

('Carb Cycling for Bodybuilders',
 'core', array[], array['core'],
 'functional', 'other', array['bodyweight'], 'advanced', false,
 'Carb cycling: alternating carbohydrate intake across different days to optimize performance, body composition, and hormonal response. Structure: (1) High carb days (~5-8 g/kg bodyweight) — heavy training days: squats, deadlifts, pressing. Goal: fuel performance and muscle protein synthesis. (2) Moderate carb days (~2-3 g/kg) — moderate training days. (3) Low carb days (~0.5-1 g/kg) — rest days or light training. Fat intake inversely adjusts to carb intake. Protein remains constant (2.2 g/kg) every day. Used extensively in contest prep and body recomposition.',
 'Eating low-carb on heavy training days (reduces performance and recovery); keeping protein too low on low-carb days (muscle loss risk); carb cycling without tracking macros (it requires precision to work); implementing during competition week for the first time (must be practiced in off-season).',
 'competition_prep', array['High carb on heavy days: your best lifts need the most fuel','Protein constant: 2.2 g/kg EVERY day regardless of carb level','Fat inversely to carbs: total calories stay consistent','Track macros: carb cycling is useless without tracking'],
 array['Advanced carb cycling with refeeds','Peak week carb manipulation protocol','Ketogenic cycling for competition prep'],
 array['Simple caloric deficit for fat loss','Maintenance eating with training','Flexible dieting (IIFYM) without periodization'],
 array['bodybuilding','competition','carb_cycling','nutrition','contest_prep','body_recomposition'], array['eating_disorder','diabetes','thyroid_disorder'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 1, null, null, null, true);
